data.text:
Whether you like his new stuff or not, Frank Miller is one of the most influential creators alive in comics. I personally lost a bit of interest somewhere between All-Star Batman & Robin and Holy Terror, but his art on the DKIII mini-comics made me pay attention again. It’s probably not as stylized as the newer generations, but his new raw style (which is mostly Miller but with a healthy dose of late Kirby inked with a rusty knife) still brings something to the table. Looking at his covers from the 70s to today there seem to be clear signs of an evolution in this direction.

There’s a reason we keep talking about Miller, while other artists of his generation seem to have left the stage, and that’s the energy he keeps putting on his art. He draws like a hungry new artist getting started in the business. And that’s, for me, a good reason to take a look back at his career through his covers. Enjoy!!!ROW #1
